</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Big Bellies have a curious notion of the Creation<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  They beleive that the world was a<span class="AddHand-editors">[ll]</span> cove<span class="AddHand-author">r</span>ed with Water upon which a swan <span class="AddHand-editors">[who]</span> unaccountably produced a Crow, a wolf and a water hen<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  One day the crow after dressing herself fine and painting her face with red and white earth paid a visit to the wolf when she observed to her host the disagreeableness of their situation surrounded with water and no one to converse with but the hen whom she thought should be sent to se<span class="DelHand-author">a</span><span class="AddHand-author">e</span> what was below the waters<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  To this the wolf consented and the hen was directed to dive &#8212; who after remaining some time under water returned with earth in her bill &#8212; which the crow taking into her hand the wolf by means of his <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Cheshequoi</span> and a Song formed into a globe such as <span class="AddHand-author">it</span> remains to this day.  <span class="AddHand-editors">[S]</span>ome time after by the same means the wolf transformed the crow into an Indian who had the singular sense of finding or making beasts, birds, fishes &amp;<sup>c</sup> so that the crow is the father of all<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  These Indians have no idea of a Supreme Being or of a future state but they say when an Indian is dead that all is over<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Intended only for</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">this</p>

